(104, 'Copyright', 'Copyright notice for Digital Orlando', '<h5>Copyright Notice</h5> \r\n<br/> All of Virginia Woolf''s published materials are out of copyright in the <br/>United States of America as of January 12th 2012. \r\n<br/> Loyola University Library holds the copies digitised. All digitisation\r\n<br/> has been done by Hannah Gillow Kloster. ', '', '', '2014-01-29 05:20:14', ''),
(105, 'Help', 'helpful information for using the site', '<h5>Helpful Information</h5>\r\n\r\n<i>This site is intended as a sample digital edition with facsimile images and searchable text as well as a basic critical apparatus.</i>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The primary material can be found directly through the vertical menu in the header. \r\nIn this menu, <strong>First British Edition</strong> refers to the First British Edition of Virginia Woolf’s Orlando, published by Hogarth Press on October 11th, 1928, while <strong>First US Trade Edition</strong> refers to the First US Trade or Regular Edition of Virginia Woolf’s Orlando, published by Harcourt Brace & Co., on October 18th, 1928.  </p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the drop-down menus from the two editions, clicking on <strong>Text</strong> will direct you to a list of pages, with links to the text of every individual page of the respective edition. Similarly, <strong>Images</strong> will take you to an image gallery of every individual page of the chosen edition. These can also be followed on to a single-page view of each individual page. When in single-page view (for text or image) a link in the left-hand sidebar, under metadata, leads to the related corresponding content, as well as to the related parallel text/image view. <p>\r\n\r\n<p> The main edition items in the vertical header menu lead to a full list of every item, text and image, associated with that particular edition.  The <strong>Parallel Text<strong/> leads to a parallel full-text view of the two versions of chapter three <p>\r\n\r\n<p>The <strong>toggler</strong> function that is visible in the parallel text/image or text/text window highlights every variant between the two editions.</p>', '', '', '2014-03-23 04:33:54', ''),
(108, 'Critical Apparatus', 'Overview over current contextual material available for Digital Orlando.', '<h5>Contextual Material </h5>\r\n\r\n<strong><ul>\r\n<li><a href="?node=content/text&id=103"> Virginia Woolf Timeline </a></li></br>\r\n<li><a href="?node=content/text&id=117">\r\nBibliography </li></br>\r\n<li><a href="?node=content/text&id=112">A note on the two editions</li>\r\n</ul><strong>\r\n\r\nThere is also some information on the mark-up process at <a href="http://digitalorlando.wordpress.com">digitalorlando.wordpress.com</a>', '', '', '2014-04-30 03:57:42', ''),
(107, 'Editions', 'An overview over current editions available', '<h5>Editions</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ol>British\r\n<li><a href="?node=taxonomy&id=9"> First edition, first impression</a> </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol> American\r\n<li><a href="?node=taxonomy&id=10"> First Trade edition, first impression</a></li>\r\n\r\n</ol>\r\n</ul>', '', '', '2014-04-06 03:03:01', ''),
(118, 'Variants', 'A brief note on variants between the editions. ', '<h5> Variants </h5>\r\n<p>I have used Juxta for initial comparison of the texts, but it is somewhat problematic using traditional collation tools when the two editions are printed from different typesets. The US edition has been typeset in the US (see link copyright), while the UK edition is typeset for Hogarth Press in the UK. This leads to the collation being somewhat thrown off by things like line breaks, page numbers, and particularly line break hyphens. Juxta reads "drinking" and "drink-ing" as two different words, making it difficult to run any kind of automatic collation on these two editions, particularly as the US edition has a particular high amount of linebreaks. A careful, manual readthrough of the collation results in Juxta has, however, resulted in discovering several significant differences between the two editions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This variants have been marked up in the same way Juxta marks up variants from two or more external witnesses, rather than locally defined variant readings or spellings: using the element &lt;app&gt; with child elements &lt;lem&gt; and &lt;rdg&gt; to define the other edition''s reading. &lt;rdg&gt; gets the attribute "wit" to define which external witness the variant originates from. This may seem superfluous in a collation/parallell text consisting only of two readings, but the benefit of this type of markup, which is essentially a hard coding of proof read collation results, is that it can easily be extended to include any further witnesses which may be added to the electronic edition at a future date.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Adding the readings from both editions has meant a certain customisation of the output has been necessary, to specify that text within &lt;lem&gt; should be output, while text within &lt;rdg&gt; should not, and is merely part of the underlying markup. A benefit of using existing TEI rather than a customised schema is of course that existing stylesheets exist for this kind of output.<p>\r\n\r\nThe variants can be seen in the <strong><a href="?node=content&id=120"> parallel text viewer</a></strong>.', '', '', '2014-04-25 17:03:40', ''),
(111, 'Why Orlando?', 'A rationale for this edition.', '<h5>A rationale for this edition </h5>\r\n<p>The initial rationale for undertaking this edition was simply that, after some research (later confirmed by Mark Hussey) that no authoritative digital text of <i>Orlando</i> seemed to be in existence, nor underway, and supported by the purely practical concern that Loyola’s library contained two of three first editions of the novel. Digital texts were, of course, available, notably <a href="http://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/w/woolf/virginia/w91o/">this edition produced by University of Adelaide</a> and the <a href="http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks02/0200331.txt">Gutenberg Project Australia</a>’s version. (Notably, they both seem to be using, based on textual variants, the US edition as their base text, though neither specify). But scholarly editions, not so much.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As the edition was undertaken, further affordances of a digital edition gradually were added. Particularly the decision to mark up the text in TEI was a choice made not only to increase the affordances of the text, but also to explore the use of TEI as annotation. Not only the contrast and similarities to TEI as annotation with traditional print annotation, but also the question of whether or not TEI annotation influences readings and use of the text more or less than the footnotes and critical apparatus of a traditional edition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The choice to use TEI was further confirmed by the particular nature of the text - the gender fluidity of the eponymous protagonist, which comes to a point in the chosen chapter, chapter 3. A further motivation was a desire to explore how to handle things like characters with more than one gender identity as well as non-linear and unreliable chronology in fiction using TEI, and the lack or not of influence these decisions may have on a reading or study using this edition. Particularly my own previous work on gender identity and sexuality in Woolf has informed my decision to make the TEI markup a significant part of this edition, rather than making it simply a two edition digital facsimile with a parallel searchable text. More on this <a href="http://digitalorlando.wordpress.com/gender/tei-politics/">here</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Exploring not only previous works and projects using TEI such as INSERT, but also theoretical explorations of the electronic edition as a scholarly edition I have been motivated by a strong conviction of the affordances the digital medium presents for researches and scholars, and the need for authoritative digital texts of seminal works such as Orlando. The digital facsimiles of the two first editions, furthermore, make these first versions of the text immediately available, supporting a study of the history of the text, and making available the version <i>Orlando</i>’s first readership were confronted with. By putting this in direct context with the first receptions of the novel, as well as loosely connected to a wider critical apparatus, this edition seeks to enhance the understanding of <em>Orlando</em>''s history. </p>', '', '', '2014-04-07 06:27:38', ''),
(112, 'About the Editions', 'A note on the different editions used for this project', '<h5> About the Editions </h5>\r\n<br/> The two editions that triggered this project were already in place in the Loyola Library Collection. These were \r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://pegasus.luc.edu/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=514722"> Woolf, Virginia: <i> Orlando: A Biography </i>, Hogarth Press (London: 1928) </a></li> and \r\n<li><a href="http://pegasus.luc.edu/vwebv/holdingsInfo?bibId=1001673"> Woolf, Virginia: <i> Orlando: A Biography </i>, Harcourt, Brace & Co. (New York, 1928)</a> </li>\r\n</ul> \r\n\r\n<p>As the library records suggest and as Loyola Archivist Kathy Young has confirmed, these are the first imprint of the British edition, published on Oct 11th 1928, and the first imprint of the US Trade or Regular edition, published on October 18th 1928. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite their relative statuses as first UK and US regular editions, neither of the editions digitised were the first version of <i>Orlando</i> to appear. 9 days before the first UK edition from the Woolfs'' own Hogarth Press, a special limited edition was published in New York by Crosby & Gaige. It is a possibility that this was done to circumvent 20th century US copyright laws with regards to foreign materials, which stipulated that for any foreign work to be within copyright by the published in the US, it must be typeset in the United States, and published in the United States prior to foreign publication. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Peter Shillingsburg has suggested this as a reason for the similar publication pattern of the first US and UK editions of Woolf''s <i>To The Lighthouse</i>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is worth making note of the correspondance between the final date of the novel (October 11th 1928) with the publication of the Hogarth Press first edition, suggesting this is, indeed, the "true" first edition. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Crosby & Gaige edition was typeset from type proofs printed by R & R Clark in Edinburgh, and corrected by Woolf before being sent to New York. These proofs were not used for the UK edition, for which no type proofs survive. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>The plates used for the Crosby & Gaige edition were then used for printing the Harcourt, Brace & co., edition, which means that though this project does not have access to images of the limited \r\nUS edition, the mark-up and text will generally speaking be similar for the the two US editions. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>The corrected type proofs have kindly been photo copied by Karen Kukil at the Mortimer Rare Book Room at Smith College, and have been temporarily included in this project. Karen, and Alison Scott in her article "Tantalising Fragments" have indicated that <i>Orlando,</i> is that of Woolf''s novels she edited the most in the span from type proof to final typeset, and though this chapter is not the most heavily marked, it shows active revision by the author. </p> ', '', '', '2014-04-17 01:45:35', ''),
(113, 'About the TEI Markup', 'A note on the TEI mark-up used for this project', '<h5> About the TEI Markup </h5>\r\n<p> The Mark-up language chosen to mark up the texts of the two editions is <a href="www.tei-c.org"> TEI </a>. Despite it''s limitations, which are discussed in this project''s <a href="http://www.digitalorlando.wordpress.com"><strong> Companion Site</strong> </a>, it is still the obvious choice for any textual scholar. Specific issues with marking up <i>Orlando</i> are brought up in the companion paper, but the most specifically complicated issue was of course that of Orlando''s gender.</p>\r\n<p>Though the TEI guidelines have recently been expanded from offering simply the gender binaries "male" and "female" [include link to appropriate guideline section], there is still not an easy way to mark one person to be of two or more genders within the same text without removing the purpose of marking up the gender. The <sex> tag as outlined in P5 is only permissable in the listPerson element, which again is only permissable in the TEI header. This means that there is no obvious way, or even "legal" way to mark up a mid-text gender shift. </p>\r\n \r\n<p> I have chosen to circumvent this issue by creating two keys for Orlando''s character throughout - OrM and OrW. These are then both included in the persList element in the header. Though this allows me to change the sex attached to Orlando''s character midway through Chapter 3, BUT sadly it indicates that Orlando also turns into a different person, with different characteristics and traits, which of course is not the case. </p> \r\n\r\n<p> One obvious other way to circumvent the gender assignment issues of TEI is to write a separate schema for <i>Orlando</i>. However, this project was in part an exploration into using TEI for modernist fiction markup, and whether it''s affordances outweigh it''s limitations, and if it''s status as the default Humanities/Textual Studies XML language is justified. These findings are discussed further at <strong><a href="http://www.digitalorlando.wordpress.com">digitalorlando.wordpress.com</a></strong> </p>.', '', '', '2014-04-17 01:45:35', ''),
(116, 'Metadata', 'Information on the site metadata', '<h5> Metadata information </h5><p> Metadata information for each image is embedded in the image itself, for download. \nUnless otherwise noted, all facsimile images are of a book belonging to the Loyola University Library, and scanned by Hannah Gillow Kloster. \nLikewise, all text transcriptions are corrected OCR-output from the same images, corrected and marked up in TEI. </p>\n', '', '', '2014-04-20 06:10:51', ''),
(117, 'Bibliography', 'An overview over related works and links. ', '<h5> Bibliography </h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.woolfonline.com">Woolfonline</a></li><br/>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/culture/2013/02/shape-shifter-joyous-transgressions-virginia-woolf%E2%80%99s-orlando">''Shape Shifter: The Joyous Transgressions of Virginia Woolf''s Orlando''</a>, Jeanette Winterson, <i>New Statesman (Feb 18th 2013)</i></li><br/>\r\n<li><a href="http://http://www.smith.edu/libraries/libs/rarebook/exhibitions/penandpress/> Woolf in the World: A Pen and Press of Her Own </a> <br/> Materials from the Elizabeth P. Richardson Bloomsbury Iconography Collection \r\nand the Frances Hooper Collection of Virginia Woolf Books and Manuscripts at Smith College</li><br/>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/books/97/06/08/reviews/woolf-orlando.html">''Mrs. Woolf Explores the "Time" Element in Human Relationships review</a>'', Cleveland B. Chase, <i>New York Times</i>(Oct 21st 1928)</li><br/>\r\n<li>”‘Tantalising Fragments'': The Proofs of Virginia Woolf''s Orlando.", Allison M. Scott, Papers of the Bibliographical Society of America 88 (1994): 279-351.</li><br/>\r\n<li><a href=”http://www.jstor.org/stable/441325”>’Orlando: An Edition of the Manuscript’</a>, Madeline Moore, <i>Twentieth Century Literature</i>, Vol. 25. No. 3/4.</li>\r\n</ul>', '', '', '2014-04-24 17:26:19', '');
